# Testing

The project uses Minitest with transactional fixtures. There is no DatabaseCleaner — fixtures roll back after each test.

## Running tests

- Run a single file:
  ```bash
  bin/rails test test/services/user/notification_digest_test.rb
  ```
- Run a single test method:
  ```bash
  bin/rails test test/services/user/notification_digest_test.rb -n test_delivers_notifications
  ```
- Always run the tests you write or modify before committing.

## Test layout

- `test/services/<module>/` — service tests. Every new service class gets a test file mirroring its path.
- `test/controllers/<module>/` — HTTP-level controller tests (no Capybara browser).
- `test/integration/<module>/` — Capybara integration tests (browser, JS, modals).
- `test/models/<module>/` — model tests.
- `test/jobs/<module>/` — background job tests.
- `test/javascript/<module>/` — Jest tests (see `javascript-tests.mdc`).
- `test/misc/i18n_test.rb` — verifies locale completeness; run after locale changes.

## Test file structure

- Start every test file with `# frozen_string_literal: true`.
- `require "test_helper"` at the top.
- Unit and service tests extend `ActiveSupport::TestCase`.
- Integration tests extend `ActionDispatch::IntegrationTest`.
- Controller tests extend `GobiertoControllerTest` (HTTP-only, request-level helpers loaded automatically).
- Use Minitest method-style: `def test_<scenario>`.
- Use `attr_reader` and `setup` rather than `@ivar` everywhere. Example:

  ```ruby
  attr_reader :user, :site

  def setup
    @site = sites(:madrid)
    @user = users(:user1)
  end
  ```

## Assertions

- Prefer Minitest's built-in assertions (`assert`, `assert_equal`, `assert_includes`, `assert_nil`, `assert_difference`, `assert_no_difference`).
- For Capybara assertions, use `assert_text`, `assert_selector`, `assert_no_selector` — these wait. Never use `sleep` to wait for the UI.
- For controller tests, assert on `response.status` and `response.body`. Use `assert_redirected_to` for redirects.

## Fixtures vs factories

- Fixtures live in `test/fixtures/<module>/` and load via `fixtures :all`.
- Factories live in `test/factories/<thing>_factory.rb` (note: not FactoryBot — these are plain Ruby classes with class methods like `BudgetLineFactory.doc_id(...)`).
- Prefer fixtures for shared baseline data (sites, admins, basic budgets). Use factories when a test needs a non-fixture variation.

## Mocking and stubbing

- Use Mocha for stubs and expectations: `object.expects(:method).returns(value)`, `object.stubs(:method).returns(value)`.
- Use Spy when checking that something was called with specific arguments and you want a richer matcher.
- Never let test concerns leak into production code. If a test object is missing a method, fix the test object — not the production class.

## VCR for HTTP interactions

VCR cassettes live in `test/vcr_cassettes/`. Wrap external HTTP calls in:

```ruby
VCR.use_cassette("path/to/scenario") do
  # code that makes the HTTP request
end
```

- Name cassettes descriptively, mirroring the test path.
- Re-record by deleting the cassette and re-running the test; review the new fixture before committing.
- WebMock is enabled globally and blocks unstubbed external requests (localhost and Elasticsearch are allowlisted).

## Time and randomness

- Use Timecop for time-sensitive tests:
  ```ruby
  Timecop.freeze(Time.zone.parse("2024-01-15"))
  # ...
  Timecop.return
  ```
  Integration tests reset Capybara automatically; in unit tests, `Timecop.return` in teardown if you set it in setup.
- Avoid relying on `Time.now`/`Date.today` in production code; inject the time when feasible so tests don't need to freeze it.

## Anti-patterns to avoid

- `sleep` in integration tests — use Capybara's waiting matchers.
- Asserting that `I18n.t("some.key")` appears on a page — that's tautological. Assert on the actual rendered text or on a behavioral element.
- Re-checking model state through Capybara after a form submit — write a model/service test for the persistence assertion and keep the integration test about the user flow.
- Disabling tests instead of fixing them. Raise the issue with a person before deleting or skipping a test.
